uts-pay-across-company-to-preserve-cash-for-investment ) :

Intel Corp., struggling with a rapid drop in revenue and earnings, is cutti=
ng management pay across the company to cope with a shaky economy and prese=
rve cash for an ambitious turnaround plan. Chief Executive Officer Pat Gels=
inger is taking a 25% cut to his base salary, the chipmaker said Tuesday. H=
is executive leadership team will see their pay packets decreased by 15%. S=
enior managers will take a 10% reduction, and the compensation for mid-leve=
l managers will be cut by 5%=E2=80=A6

Gelsinger will keep using cash to reward shareholders, meanwhile. Intel sai=
d last week that it remains committed to offering a competitive dividend. A=
nalysts have speculated that the company may lower its payout to cope with =
the slowdown.

Dylan Patel at SemiAnalysis ( https://www.semianalysis.com/p/intel-cuts-pay=
-for-employees-to-keep ) says more is being cut than just executive base co=
mpensation:

Hot off the presses, we have confirmation from multiple employees that Inte=
l is cutting costs tremendously at the expense of their employees. These cu=
ts are broad-based, with employees having their compensation affected. Quar=
terly pay bonuses are gone, annual bonuses are being paused, 401k match is =
halved from 5% to 2.5%, merit-based raises are suspended, and there is a pa=
y cut to all employees=E2=80=99 base salary based on grade.

All employees below Principal Engineer, grades 7 to 11, will get a 5% cut, =
10% cuts will be instituted for VPs, and the executive leadership team will=
 take a 15% cut, with Pat Gelsinger taking a 25% cut. These cuts hurt even =
more when we are in an inflationary environment. These cost cuts are, of co=
urse, dwarfed by their quarterly dividend, of course, which we have been cl=
amoring for them to cut for over a year.

I defended paying a dividend, if not one of the current size, in Monday=E2=
=80=99s Update ( https://stratechery.com/2023/intel-earnings-intels-plungin=
g-margin-the-dividend-question/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6=
InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdG=
VjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlc=
nkuY29tLzIwMjMvaW50ZWwtZWFybmluZ3MtaW50ZWxzLXBsdW5naW5nLW1hcmdpbi10aGUtZGl2=
aWRlbmQtcXVlc3Rpb24vIl19LCJleHAiOjE2Nzc4NDk0OTIsImlhdCI6MTY3NTI1NzQ5MiwiaXN=
zIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9zdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6Im=
ZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIiwic3ViIjoiU=
nNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.hv60Rbg8rBIWeX7ZxIfAWNq=
5qrz8dvsCV08QS99k9TAXxRFhGCNhZoeVVe6BQ8L5VfVMq_pst61XuRMgOUh9b75RKJI5Dhhlcw=
gr_oVcjVGwI7LVv4NuEPUJ2Lxcb2p0WbQtmZdhjQz3-RTKb3T7MQs9EdCvGM1l-mwbmVIsTaNvQ=
0V6ne0gqmWfnyqz8zN0k8EBbTIXa9e3D5mpBgxW0R7ivg_-t33KHdM4n1BigvZJY6h3QZcfRXAV=
SfIVxCvlamh7NAYLW0fUcnUbf77aA4m0-Xc9NMlUb2N9pgYRBgUN-IrzG4_xoxA5u5p_1ybrJ6M=
DjBWuuvlfIkWsI__vqw ). I noted that Intel=E2=80=99s stock appreciated a lot=
 even as the company=E2=80=99s core business drifted into crisis, and made =
the case that even if Intel was headed in the right direction now, good res=
ults would take a long time to materialize, and that there was a good case =
for Intel to reward the investors who stayed with the company.

I=E2=80=99m officially changing my mind: I think I was wrong.

Let=E2=80=99s review the situation: Intel is in a major hole. It has too mu=
ch capacity for what it is able to sell currently. It is getting beaten by =
AMD in the data center, in an environment in which cloud spending is slowin=
g. The consumer market is dead after a massive COVID pull-forward in sales.=
 Meanwhile, Intel is undertaking two massive projects: first, the company i=
s trying to catch up to and surpass TSMC in terms of process. Second, the c=
ompany is trying to build a foundry business to fill up those very expensiv=
e fabs it is building. The first challenge is exceptionally difficult, but =
if Intel has any of the old Intel left, doable; the second is arguably even=
 harder, precisely because the old Intel is an obstacle to building a modul=
ar customer-centric service organization. None of this is easy, nor is it g=
uaranteed to be a success.

In short, to succeed in this transformation, Intel will need more than the =
leadership of Pat Gelsinger: they will need the ingenuity, industriousness,=
 and incredibly hard work of every one of its employees. Indeed, a successf=
ul turnaround will be so dramatic and so valuable that the contribution of =
every single employee that made it possible will have turned out to be inva=
luable.

This is not, to be sure, a defense of every Intel employee; like everyone e=
lse in the space I have heard the stories about how Intel has lost thousand=
s of good employees, and retained far too many who would have trouble findi=
ng an equivalent job elsewhere, particularly the higher up you go in the ma=
nagement chain. After all, those were the very people who were at Intel whe=
n the company was going into the ditch. To that end, I think a significant =
reduction in force, on top of the one already taken, would likely be justif=
iable.

A blanket cut in compensation, though, seems like the worst possible way to=
 address any perceived employee cost issues: Intel is going to penalize the=
 valuable employees just as much as they are the ones that are hanging on o=
r, worse, fighting to keep Intel on its old path; were I one of the former,=
 I would not only probably be more employable outside of Intel, I would now=
 be significantly more motivated to put that supposition to the test. What =
I would not be motivated about is sacrificing not just money but tremendous=
 effort for an uncertain outcome for a company that has demonstrated it can=
=E2=80=99t be bothered to determine who deserves a pay cut, and who does no=
t.

Of course this approach does have the advantage of cutting costs, and quick=
ly; so would cutting the dividend. Indeed, one of the reasons to be concern=
ed about maintaining the stock is for employee equity reasons, but that kin=
d of seems like a pointless concern at this point.

Investor Honesty
----------------

This pay cut isn=E2=80=99t the only reason I changed my mind. I thought tha=
t MetaCritic Capital ( https://twitter.com/MetacriticCap ) cut to the heart=
 of the matter in a Twitter thread:

( https://twitter.com/MetacriticCap/status/1620091300447158273?ref_src=3Dtw=
src%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1620091300447158273%7Ctwgr%5E7f7=
e4f5a42b33d5a670636476a306a17cb03a6d1%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&ref_url=3Dhttp%3A%2F%2F=
chrome-headless.local%3A9222%2Fatomic )

It=E2=80=99s difficult to not look back at what I wrote and come to a simil=
ar conclusion: my solution for Intel prioritizing its investors and not bei=
ng honest about its business for the last 15 years is to=E2=80=A6prioritize=
 its investors and not be honest with them about its business for the next =
five years. That=E2=80=99s terrible advice when you put it that way, and ye=
t very much in line with exactly how Intel has operated for quite awhile no=
w.

As I noted on Monday, Intel had two choices when Gelsinger took over:

* Figure out a way to spin out the fabs and become a fabless chip designer =
like AMD (as I proposed in 2021 ( https://stratechery.com/2021/intel-proble=
ms/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0=
Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbm=
