XO6xOLgI1TksR8ox0u5VslksRosswIlTQCR-tC_Eyjr-COsLdN4a_T6jqzDyfJGJHJJQP0v20L4=
4_iwfg ) ); TSMC would have taken the business, and Intel would no longer b=
e bleeding in the data center in particular. This would have been difficult=
, to be sure =E2=80=94 Intel would have probably had to make long-term comm=
itments to the fabs to get them off of the ground =E2=80=94 but it would ha=
ve been the surest route to higher margins and maintaining market share. It=
 also would have been compatible with keeping the dividend.

* 

Develop a real foundry business that leveraged Intel=E2=80=99s IDM business=
 as the first best customer to compete with TSMC. This is the route Gelsing=
er took and it is, for the reasons I laid out above, an exceptionally diffi=
cult one. At the same time, it is also the route with the highest long-term=
 upside. However =E2=80=94 and this is the point I should have realized on =
Monday =E2=80=94 this course of action is incompatible with continuing to p=
ay the dividend.

I respect Gelsinger=E2=80=99s decision to go for choice two, even if one ca=
n make the case that he is perhaps blinded by his Intel roots and desire to=
 regain its legacy as the best chipmaker in the world. What I missed, thoug=
h, is that Gelsinger needed to be honest with investors about the implicati=
ons of that choice. That would have meant suspending the dividend when he a=
nnounced IDM 2.0 ( https://stratechery.com/2021/intel-unleashed-gelsinger-o=
n-intel-idm-2-0/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ=
5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzc=
G9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkuY29tLzIwMjEv=
aW50ZWwtdW5sZWFzaGVkLWdlbHNpbmdlci1vbi1pbnRlbC1pZG0tMi0wLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNjc=
